issue.title: Do not use reflect when writing plain array columns
issue.body: **Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.** In my application I mostly write big plain string arrays to CH e.g. `[]string`. I noticed, that using of reflection is responsible for 28% of all the allocations and at least 5% of cpu usage in my app. **Describe the solution you'd like** I believe it is possible to get rid of reflection here, at least for the plain arrays. I have a draft proof of concept of what I think would work fine here: #1121

comment.body: Unfortunately it did not help to reduce allocations 😔️️️️️️ There is still an allocation per every element in the slice when it is casted from `T` to `any` in `appendRowPlain`, I missed that. Will think how to avoid that and come back with a new issue.

issue.title: Can't scan an array of non-`string` custom types
issue.body:
<!-- delete unnecessary items -->
### Describe the bug

Can't read (ie., scan) an array of custom types when those custom types don't define the `string` type.

As you can observe in the reproducer below:

1. Writing/reading an array of a `string` custom type works
    * ie., `[]SomeString` -> `Array(LowCardinality(String))`
2. Writing/reading a custom type defining a type different than `string` work implementing `sql.Scanner` and `fmt.Stringer`
    * ie., `SomeUint64AsString` -> `String`
3. Reading an array of a custom type defining some type other than `string` **doesn't work**
    * writing works
    * can't scan values back
    * ie., `[]SomeUint64AsString` -> `Array(LowCardinality(String))`
    * See `Test3` field in the reproducer
    * Errors with `clickhouse [ScanRow]: (Col3) converting string to main.SomeUint64AsString is unsupported`

Sending a pull request with a fix soon.

I've also found that reading an array of pointers to a custom type **doesn't work** (see `Test4` and `Test5` fields in the reproducer), but maybe that's a topic for another issue/PR.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Write an array of non-`string` custom type
2. Try to scan them back

### Expected behavior

I'd expect it to work just like it works for non-array custom types (see `Test2` field in the reproducer).

I'd expect the reproducer to output:

```
row: col={[one two] A [B C]}
```

For this to happen, the function [`setJSONFieldValue`](https://github.com/ClickHouse/clickhouse-go/blob/cdbdd90029a211d3591ab94ea94c4b5545636022/lib/column/tuple.go#L146) should check if the target implements `sql.Scanner` (and call the `Scan` method), in a way similar to what the [string.go](https://github.com/ClickHouse/clickhouse-go/blob/cdbdd90029a211d3591ab94ea94c4b5545636022/lib/column/string.go#L77) file does.

### Code example

Here's a reproducer.

```go
package main

import (
	"context"
	"fmt"

	"github.com/ClickHouse/clickhouse-go/v2"
)

const (
	A SomeUint64AsString = iota + 1
	B
	C
	D
	E
)

type SomeUint64AsString uint64

// Scan implements sql.Scanner for the type SomeUint64AsString.
func (f *SomeUint64AsString) Scan(src any) error {
	if t, ok := src.(uint64); ok {
		*f = SomeUint64AsString(t)
		return nil
	}
	if t, ok := src.(string); ok {
		switch t {
		case "A":
			*f = A
		case "B":
			*f = B
		case "C":
			*f = C
		default:
			return fmt.Errorf("cannot scan %s into SomeUint64AsString", t)
		}
		return nil
	}

	return fmt.Errorf("cannot scan %T into SomeUint64AsString", src)
}

func (f SomeUint64AsString) String() string {
	switch f {
	case A:
		return "A"
	case B:
		return "B"
	case C:
		return "C"
	}
	return ""
}

type SomeString string

func (s SomeString) String() string {
	return string(s)
}

func InsertAndRead() error {
	opts := &clickhouse.Options{
		Settings: clickhouse.Settings{},
	}

	conn, err := clickhouse.Open(opts)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}
	ctx := context.Background()

	conn.Exec(ctx, "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS example")

	if err = conn.Exec(ctx, `
		CREATE TABLE example (
				Col1 Array(LowCardinality(String))
			, 	Col2 String
			,	Col3 Array(LowCardinality(String))
			//,	Col4 Array(LowCardinality(String))
			//, 	Col5 String
		)
		Engine Memory
		`); err != nil {
		return err
	}

	type Test struct {
		Test1 []SomeString         `ch:"Col1"` // Works
		Test2 SomeUint64AsString   `ch:"Col2"` // Works
		Test3 []SomeUint64AsString `ch:"Col3"` // DOESN'T WORK
		// Test4 []*SomeString        `ch:"Col4"` // DOESN'T WORK TOO
		// Test5 *SomeUint64AsString  `ch:"Col5"` // DOESN'T WORK TOO
	}

	defer func() {
		conn.Exec(ctx, "DROP TABLE example")
	}()
	batch, err := conn.PrepareBatch(ctx, "INSERT INTO example")
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}

	colData := Test{
		Test1: []SomeString{"one", "two"},
		Test2: A,
		Test3: []SomeUint64AsString{B, C},
		// Test4: []*SomeString{func() *SomeString { x := SomeString("three"); return &x }()},
		// Test5: func() *SomeUint64AsString { x := E; return &x }(),
	}
	// both named and unnamed can be added with slices
	if err = batch.AppendStruct(&colData); err != nil {
		return err
	}

	if err = batch.Send(); err != nil {
		return err
	}

	var (
		col Test
	)
	// named tuples can be retrieved into a map or slices, unnamed just slices
	if err = conn.QueryRow(ctx, "SELECT * FROM example").ScanStruct(&col); err != nil {
		return err
	}
	fmt.Printf("row: col=%v\n", col)

	return nil
}

func main() {
	if err := InsertAndRead(); err != nil {
		fmt.Println(err)
	}
}
```

### Error log

`clickhouse [ScanRow]: (Col3) converting string to main.SomeUint64AsString is unsupported`

### Configuration
#### Environment
* Client version: 23.9.1.1854 (official build)
* Language version: github.com/ClickHouse/clickhouse-go/v2 v2.14.3
* OS: Darwin 23.0.0 arm64
* Interface: ClickHouse API

#### ClickHouse server
* ClickHouse Server version: 23.9.1 revision 54466
* ClickHouse Server non-default settings, if any: NONE
* `CREATE TABLE` statements for tables involved: NONE
